y criticism in order, ultimately, to develop an original theory of literary production. Along the way, it offers new readings of major modernist novels by Samuel Beckett, Marcel Proust, and Gertrude Stein.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aGertude Stein.  aGilles Deleuze.  aIndividuation.  aMarcel Proust.  aModernism.  aModernist Novel.  aNewness.  aSamuel Beckett.  arhetoric.  aromanticism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823270088zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823270088423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823270088/original  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK